{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565133"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:23:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:23:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17208"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17208"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.13,0.05,0.11,0.69]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9898"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107223"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9898"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17208"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89678"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1880"},{"type":"tags","id":"2240"},{"type":"tags","id":"2615"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9736"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23220"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39718"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43692"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107223"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with three weeks of worsening breathlessness and peripheral oedema. She has no chest pain. She has severe chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) with an FEV1 of 35% predicted, diagnosed 15 years ago. She uses regular tiotropium and fluticasone/vilanterol inhaler. She continues to smoke 15 cigarettes per day and has had three hospital admissions in the past year for COPD exacerbations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears short of breath at rest. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Her jugular venous pressure is elevated at 8 cm. There is peripheral oedema to the mid-shin. Chest auscultation reveals reduced air entry bilaterally. Heart sounds are normal with a loud P2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest X-ray shows hyperinflated lung fields and prominent pulmonary arteries. ECG shows right axis deviation and right ventricular strain pattern. Blood tests reveal normal full blood count, electrolytes, and troponin.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her deterioration?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute coronary syndrome","Acute COPD exacerbation","Acute pulmonary embolism","Left ventricular failure","Pulmonary hypertension"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of right heart failure in the setting of severe COPD. The combination of worsening dyspnoea, peripheral oedema, elevated jugular venous pressure, and ECG changes pointing to right heart strain strongly suggests the development of \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E as a complication of her chronic lung disease (Group 3 pulmonary hypertension).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents more acutely with sudden onset dyspnoea and pleuritic chest pain. While it can cause right heart strain, the gradual onset over three weeks makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft ventricular failure\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with orthopnoea, paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnoea, and basal crepitations. The presence of a loud P2 and right ventricular strain on ECG points more towards right-sided heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute COPD exacerbation\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with increased cough, sputum production, and wheeze. While this may be present, these features alone don\u0027t explain the signs of right heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute coronary syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely given the absence of chest pain, normal troponin, and the presence of clear signs of right heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary hypertension is a common complication in advanced COPD, occurring in up to 50% of patients with severe disease. The mechanism involves chronic hypoxic vasoconstriction, inflammation, and loss of pulmonary vasculature due to emphysema. The development of cor pulmonale signifies a poor prognosis and requires careful management of the underlying COPD and consideration of specific therapies for pulmonary hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pulmonary hypertension is a common complication of chronic lung disease, particularly in advanced cases.","Signs of right heart failure in a patient with chronic lung disease should prompt consideration of pulmonary hypertension.","The combination of increasing dyspnoea, peripheral oedema, and elevated jugular venous pressure suggests right heart failure."],"references":["Elwing J, Panos RJ. Pulmonary hypertension associated with COPD. International journal of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. 2008 Jan 1;3(1):55-70. Available from: https://www.dovepress.com/articles.php?article_id=567","Blanco I, Tura-Ceide O, Peinado VI, Barber\u00e0 JA. Updated perspectives on pulmonary hypertension in COPD. International Journal of Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease. 2020 Jun 9:1315-24. Available from: https://dx.doi.org/10.2147/COPD.S211841"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89678"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17208"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89678"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-26T14:54:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-26T14:57:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9898"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107223"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},